Vladimir Putin and the risk of a Third World War
SAN FRANCISCO – Russia's invasion of Ukraine on February 24 marked the beginning of a third world war that has the potential to destroy our civilization.
The invasion was preceded by a long meeting between Russian President Vladimir Putin and Chinese President Xi Jinping on February 4 – at the beginning of Chinese Lunar New Year celebrations and the Beijing Winter Olympics.
At the end of this meeting, the two men published a 5,000-word document, carefully written, announcing a close partnership between their two countries.
The document is stronger than any treaty and certainly required meticulous preparatory negotiations.
I was surprised to see that Xi seems to have given carte blanche to Putin to invade and go to war against Ukraine.
He must be very confident and consider his later confirmation as lifelong leader of China a mere formality.
After concentrating all powers in his hands, Xi carefully prepared the scenario according to which he will be elevated to the level of Mao Zedong and Deng Xiaoping.
After obtaining Xi's support, Putin undertook to realize his life's dream with incredible brutality.
As Putin approaches his 70s, he thinks that if he wants to impose his mark on Russian history, now is the time or never.
But his conception of Russia's role in the world is distorted.
It seems to him that the Russian people need a tsar they can follow blindly.
That is precisely the opposite of a democratic society - and it's a vision that distorts the "soul" of Russia, emotional to the point of sentimentality.
As a child, I have met Russian soldiers many times when they occupied Hungary in 1945.
I learned that they were willing to share their last piece of bread with you if you ask them.
Later, at the beginning of the 1980s, I embarked on what I call my political philanthropy.
First, I created a foundation in my native Hungary, then I actively participated in the disintegration of the Soviet empire.
When Mikhail Gorbachev came to power in 1985, the disintegration had already begun.
I created a foundation in Russia, then I did the same in each of the successor states.
In Ukraine, I created a foundation even before it became an independent country.
I also visited China in 1984, where I was the first foreigner allowed to establish a foundation (which I closed in 1989, just before the Tiananmen Square massacre).
I don't know Putin personally, but I have closely observed his rise, being aware of his cruelty.
He has reduced the Chechen capital of Grozny to nothing. And he threatens to do the same with the Ukrainian capital of Kyiv.
Putin was once a cunning operator of the KGB, but he seems to have changed lately.
Having developed a fixed idea, he seems to have lost touch with reality.
He certainly underestimated the situation in Ukraine.
He expected the Russian-speaking Ukrainians to welcome Russian soldiers with open arms, but they turned out to be entirely on the same positions as the Ukrainian-speaking population.
The Ukrainians have set up an incredibly courageous resistance against an opponent that seems to be unstoppable.
In July 2021, Putin published a long essay arguing that the Russians and Ukrainians are really one people and that the Ukrainians have been misled by neo-Nazi agitators.
The first part of his argument is not entirely without historical justification, given that Kyiv was the original seat of the Russian Orthodox Church.
But in the second part, it's Putin who was misled.
He should have been more cautious.
Many Ukrainians fought bravely during the 2014 'Euromaidan demonstrations.
The 2014 events plunged him into a black anger.
But the Russian army made a poor figure when it received the order to attack its Ukrainian brothers.
The entrenched corruption in the awarding of defense contracts has also played an important role in its insufficient results.
Yet, rather than blaming himself, Putin seems to have literally gone mad.
He has decided to punish Ukraine for opposing him and appears to be acting without encountering any resistance.
He unleashes all the Russian army into battle and ignores all the rules of war, including indiscriminately bombing the civilian population.
Many hospitals have been hit and the power grid supplying the Chernobyl nuclear power plant (currently occupied by Russian troops) has been damaged.
In the besieged Mariupol, 400,000 people were left without water and food for nearly a week.
Russia could well lose the war.
The United States and the European Union are sending defensive arms to Ukraine, and efforts are underway to buy Russian-made MIG fighter jets that Ukrainian pilots know how to fly.
This could make all the difference.
Whatever the outcome, Putin has already done wonders in strengthening the determination and unity of the EU.
Meanwhile, Xi seems to have realized that Putin is flying solo.
On March 8, a day after Chinese Foreign Minister Wang Yi insisted that Sino-Russian friendship remains 'solid', Xi called French President Emmanuel Macron and German Chancellor Olaf Scholz to express his support for their efforts to restore peace.
He wanted to show maximum restraint in the war to avoid a humanitarian crisis.
It's far from certain that Putin will heed Xi's wishes.
We can only hope that Putin and Xi will be ousted before they destroy our civilization.
